definition.value: A 1,4-benzodiazepinone that is 1,3-dihydro-2H-1,4-benzodiazepin-2-one substituted by a chloro group at position 7, a hydroxy group at position 3 and phenyl group at position 5.
A bile acid anion that is the conjugate base of ursodeoxycholic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A cyclic nonapeptide hormone with amino acid sequence CYIQNCPLG that also acts as a neurotransmitter in the brain; the principal uterine-contracting and milk-ejecting hormone of the posterior pituitary. Together with the neuropeptide vasopressin, it is believed to influence social cognition and behaviour.
A ketohexose monophosphate consisting of fructose having a phosphate group located at the 1-position
A nineteen carbon straight-chain fatty acid anion. Major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty acid anion with 22 carbons and 2 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion containing 22 carbons and 3 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
A long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of hexadecanoic acid (palmitic acid); major species at pH 7.3.
A monounsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of (10Z)-heptadecenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of pantothenic acids that is an amide formed from pantoic acid and beta-alanine.

A benzodioxole that consists of piperidine bearing 1,3-benzodioxol-5-yloxy)methyl and 4-fluorophenyl substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively; the (3S,4R)-diastereomer. Highly potent and selective 5-HT uptake inhibitor that binds with high affinity to the serotonin transporter (Ki = 0.05 nM). Ki values are 1.1, 350 and 1100 nM for inhibition of [3H]-5-HT, [3H]-l-NA and [3H]-DA uptake respectively. Displays minimal affinity for alpha1-, alpha2- or beta-adrenoceptors, 5-HT2A, 5-HT1A, D2 or H1 receptors at concentrations below 1000 nM, however displays weak affinity for muscarinic ACh receptors (Ki = 42 nM). Antidepressant and anxiolytic in vivo.
A sesquiterpene lactone and active principle of Feverfew (Tanacetum parthenium).
An optically active form of penicillamine having D-configuration. Pharmaceutical form (L-form is toxic) of chelating agent used to treat heavy metal poisoning.

A methanesulfonate salt obtained from pergolide by mixing eqimolar amount of pergolide and methanesulfonic acid. A dopamine D2 receptor agonist which also has D1 and D2 agonist properties, it is used in the management of Parkinson's disease, although it was withdrawn from the U.S. and Canadian markets in 2007 due to an increased risk of cardiac valve dysfunction.
A phenothiazine derivative in which the phenothiazine tricycle carries a chloro substituent at the 2-position and a 3-[4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]propyl group at N-10.
A member of the class of acetamides that is acetamide in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 4-ethoxyphenyl group.

A member of the class of piperidines that is piperidine in which the nitrogen is substituted with a 1-phenylcyclohexyl group.  Formerly used as an anaesthetic agent, it exhibits both hallucinogenic and neurotoxic effects.

A member of the class of pyranoindolizinoquinolines that is the carbamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of [1,4'-bipiperidine]-1'-carboxylic acid with the phenolic hydroxy group of (4S)-4,11-diethyl-4,9-dihydroxy-1H-pyrano[3',4':6,7]indolizino[1,2- hydrochloride]quinoline-3,14-dione. Used (in the form of its hydrochloride salt trihydrate) in combination with fluorouracil and leucovorin, for the treatment of patients with metastatic adenocarcinoma of the pancreas after disease progression following gemcitabine-based therapy. It is converted via hydrolysis of the carbamate linkage to its active metabolite, SN-38, which is ~1000 times more active.
A member of the class of barbiturates, the structure of which is that of barbituric acid substituted at C-5 by ethyl and phenyl groups.
A member of the class of the class of phenylethanolamines that is (1R)-2-(methylamino)-1-phenylethan-1-ol carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 3 on the phenyl ring.
A 2-hydroxy carboxylate that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-phenyllactic acid.
A imidazolidine-2,4-dione that consists of hydantoin bearing two phenyl substituents at position 5.
A trihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at the 3alpha-, 6alpha- and 7alpha-positions.

A member of the class of benzimidazoles that is 1,3-dihydro-2H-benzimidazol-2-one in which one of the nitrogens is substituted by a piperidin-4-yl group, which in turn is substituted on the nitrogen by a 4,4-bis(p-fluorophenyl)butyl group.

A member of the class of thiazolidenediones that is 1,3-thiazolidine-2,4-dione substituted by a benzyl group at position 5 which in turn is substituted by a 2-(5-ethylpyridin-2-yl)ethoxy group at position 4 of the phenyl ring. It exhibits hypoglycemic activity.
A cholesterol ester obtained by the formal condensation of the hydroxy group in cholesterol with the carboxy group of stearic acid.
An organic sulfate of thymol.
A glycine derivative that is the carboxamide obtained by the formal condensation of the amino group of glycine with 2-furoic acid.
A L-tyrosine derivative that is the 3-methoxy derivative of L-dopa.
An aryl sulfate that is p-cresol in which the phenolic hydrogen has been replaced by a sulfo group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(1H-indol-3-yl)propanoic acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as palmitoyl and linoleoyl respectively.
An  aryl sulfate that is 4-hydroxystyrene in which the hydroxy group has been replaced by a sulfooxy group.
An aryl sulfate that is 4-ethylphenol in which the hydroxy group has been replaced by a sulfooxy group.
An aryl sulfate that is the 3-hydroxy derivative of  paracetamol sulfate.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-methionine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of glutamic acid and phenylalanine joined together by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of glutamic acid and  threonine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-tyrosine joined by a peptide linkage.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-paliperidone. Paliperidone is the primary active metabolite of the older antipsychotic risperidone and is used for treatment of schizophrenia.
A N-acylglycinate that is the  conjugate base of glycodeoxycholic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of 2-(2-carboxyethyl)-4-methyl-5-propylfuran-3-carboxylic acid.
A cholestanoid that is cholest-4-en-26-oic acid substituted by an alpha-hydroxy group at position 7 and an oxo group at position 3. It is an intermediate metabolite in the bile acid synthesis.
A steroid sulfate that is the 3-sulfate of androsterone.
A steroid sulfate that is the 3-sulfate of epiandrosterone.
An undecenoate that is the conjugate base of 10-undecenoic acid.
